Germany: A Budgetary Favourite That Comes at a High Cost
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is facing intense backlash in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on defending the principle of the independence of the central bank.
It was Germany that insisted on having this principle included in the criteria outlined by the Maastricht Treaty, which sets the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), the decision to grant independence to their central bank in order to join the eurozone implied a change in political regime.
Thus, the independence of the Bank of France, during the ratification referendum on the Maastricht Treaty in 1992, was one of the strongest arguments in the campaign against joining the euro.
In today's Germany, on the other hand, it has become common practice, if you will, to pressure the central bank.
For several months now, even the Minister of Finance, Wolfgang Schaüble, has regularly commented on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schaüble's interventions target the very heart of what constitutes the independence of the central bank.
Even if he does not seek to redefine the monetary policy objective (this "price norm," in the old jargon of the Bundesbank), he nonetheless lavishes advice on the tools the ECB should use and how it should handle them to achieve such a goal.
We know precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then Germany's Minister of Finance, offered his good advice to the first president of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's goal was to ultimately create a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with typically Dutch laconism, replied that there was nothing incongruous about a politician sharing their opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, it was absolutely unusual).

The respect for the independence of monetary policy has long been a central element of Germany's Stabilitätkultur ("culture of stability").
The founding act of the Bundesbank's reputation for strict independence was its refusal to yield to Chancellor Konrad Adenauer's exhortations to curb the rise in interest rates in 1956.
At this time, France did not see things in the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was on the verge of creating the Fifth Republic, with a Bank of France that reported to the Minister of Finance.
But it was another time.
Following the various crises that have shaken the UEM, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace budgetary policy.
Is the old dogma now obsolete?
The Europe remains very vulnerable; the median inhabitant of the UEM has already lost ten years, and what is even more worrisome, we are close to the critical situation.
The United States, on the other hand, are doing better.
Notwithstanding a difficult-to-manage political deadlock, they have succeeded in tackling the macroeconomic problem (the weakness of global demand) they were facing by launching expansionary budgetary and monetary policies.
The United States have also better managed their banking problems, which were initially much more serious than in Europe.
(There is, of course, a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in both areas.
The more robust an economy is, the more profitable its banks are, and the better they can fulfill their function: to finance the economy.)
But the independence of the ECB is less threatened by good advice from a Minister of Finance than by the lack of support from the population.
In fact, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank relied less on its legal status than on the unwavering support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
It is exactly the opposite with the ECB.
Voices are being heard, particularly in Germany, to subject it to more pressure.
But the biggest threat to the ECB's autonomy is the unbearable burden it has to bear.
The less budgetary policy is solicited to stabilize production, the more central banks are de facto forced to take on this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let nature take its course, and allow the economy to stagnate, or worse).
The political result of this chain of events is a very clear regression to nationalism, on the right and the left, in all UEM countries, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the policies pursued.
It is endogenous.
And here, Germany is also leading the dance, with its obsession with schwarze Null, budget balance, against wind and tide.
In Germany, deficits are viewed unfavorably, not only from an arithmetic point of view but also morally, even if this defies economic common sense and resembles clientelism.
In the late 19th century, the leading German specialists in public finance, including Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, forged a "golden rule" whereby current expenditures were to be funded, on average, by current revenues.
Public spending, and the resources it requires, are justified by their utility.
Which comes down to saying that investments aimed at improving productivity - equipment expenditures - can be financed with debt, whose service is ensured by the growth of income and the tax base associated with it.
This classic line of conduct was institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenditures and investment expenditures, which is still practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and in Austria).
This is crucial, because in Germany, approximately 50% of public sector investment expenditures are managed at this level (a declining proportion, since the municipal share was two-thirds at the beginning of the 1990s).
These expenditures are consistent with supporting the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (mittelstand).
However, compared to the beginning of the 1990s and adjusted for constant prices, investment expenditures have declined by approximately 15%.
It has been over a decade that they are insufficient to maintain the capital stock.
If this is not how we prepare the future, it is how we undermine productivity and prosperity.
In short, black zero is counterproductive.
The outdated infrastructure (not as outdated as in the United States) has become a real problem for Germany.
Furthermore, the budgetary thriftiness of German leaders spills over beyond German borders and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which lacks an exchange rate to acclimate national particularities.
Of course, the European Monetary Union is imperfect.
But transforming the only institution ready to "do what needs to be done" to get the EMU back on track into a scapegoat is a very bad idea.
It would be a much better strategy if the states used, where they exist, the budgetary space they have available to relieve the pressure on the ECB.
Germany, without a doubt, has some room for maneuver in this regard.
